<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-086-300 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 075 449</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  August 5 1991 v10 n16 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tiara, new 10Net owner, pledges stronger support for network OS.andO;(Tiara Computer Systems Inc., 10Net Communications, networkoperating system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Olsen, Florence.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   10NET Communications (Management)m Tiara Computer Systems Inc. (Acquisitions, mergers, divestments)Digital Communications Associates Inc. (Acquisitions, mergers,divestments).andO;Ticker:    DCA.andO;Topic:     Network operating systemsUnited States. Air ForcePeer-to-Peer CommunicationsSupport ServicesMilitary.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The new owner of 10Net Communications is pledging more support for thepeer-to-peer network operating system the Air Force chose last year for itsmilitary bases around the world.andM;Tiara Computer Systems Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., bought the 10NetCommunications business last month from Digital Communications Associates(DCA) Inc. for $2.5 million.andM;Andrei Glasberg, chief executive officer of Tiara, said in an interview that10Net &quot;perhaps suffered a little from inattention&quot; under DCA but that Tiarais prepared to support 10Net and market the product aggressively.andM;&quot;Peer-to-peer operating software is a hot market,&quot; he said, &quot;but an operatingsystem requires hand-holding, much more so than hardware.&quot;andM;A manager for the company that is providing 10Net to the Air Force under aFebruary 1990 local area network contract said the Air Force now has 7,000networked microcomputers running 10Net.andP;  But sales have been &quot;very slow,&quot;said Larry Batstone, LAN OS project manager for systems integrator FederalSystems Group Inc. of Vienna, Va.andM;The Defense Logistics Agency, which also can buy through the Air Force LAN OScontract, has placed no orders to date.andM;A number of potential Air Force and DLA buyers have said they will wait forthe next 10Net release, Version 4.3, before buying LAN software, Batstonesaid.andP;  The Air Force Standard Systems Center at Gunter Air Force Base, Ala.,andO;is evaluating the new release before approving it for the LAN OS contract.andM;Batstone said Version 4.3 is more tightly integrated with the ATandamp;T Model 3B2midrange computers the Air Force has bought from the large requirementscontract it awarded to ATandamp;T Co. in 1988.andP;  Version 4.3 has a more-efficientprint spooler and makes a seamless connection to printers attached to 3B2s,Batstone said.andM;Tiara plans to consolidate the technical support staffs of 10Net in Dayton,Ohio, and Tiara in Mountain View and to operate both as one company.andP;  &quot;Tiarahas very strong technical support, and we intend to combine both technicalsupport groups,&quot; Glasberg said.andP;  &quot;My first concern is that customers aresatisfied and that orders continue to flow.&quot;andM;10Net is known in government circles as a secure peer-to-peer LAN.andM;About the $2.5 million price tag for the 10Net Communications business,Glasberg said: &quot;If we look at that as the price of admission, the question ishow much more do we have to pay to stay in the theater.andP;  Let me reserve ananswer until six months or a year from now,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;If we do very well,then it's a bargain.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>